Barclays, Rolls-Royce, SVG Capital: U.K., Irish Equity Preview

-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t   a n d   J a c k   J o r d a n
-- 
2011-02-14T07:45:25Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-13/barclays-rolls-royce-svg-capital-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  The benchmark  FTSE 100 Index  advanced 42.89 points, or 0.7
percent, to 6,062.9. The FTSE All-Share Index gained 0.7
percent, and Ireland’s ISEQ Index rose 1.2 percent.    Allied Irish Banks Plc  (ALBK ID): Irish Life & Permanent
Plc is about to enter exclusive talks to buy the asset
management unit of Allied Irish, the Sunday Times said, without
citing anyone. The shares jumped 4.1 percent to 28.1 euro cents.    Avanti Communications Group Plc  (AVN LN): The U.K.
satellite service provider said first-half sales fell to 1.2
million pounds ($1.9 million) from 3.3 million pounds a year
earlier. The stock advanced 3.7 percent to 605 pence.    Barclays Plc  (BARC LN): Britain’s third-largest bank is
poised to double its annual dividend to more than 570 million
pounds, the Sunday Express reported. The shares fell 0.7 percent
to 311.1 pence.    BP Plc  (BP/ LN): TNK-BP’s Russian billionaire shareholders
will likely demand at a board meeting next week that the venture
participate in BP’s planned alliance with OAO Rosneft, the
Financial Times reported. The stock declined 0.2 percent to
475.75 pence.  Fidessa Group Plc (FDSA LN): The U.K. financial software
developer whose customers include Deutsche Bank AG said pretax
profit rose 28 percent last year to 39.7 million pounds as
revenue increased 10 percent. The shares rose 4 percent to 1,700
pence.  International Consolidated Airlines Group SA (IAG LN):
British Airways’ parent company ousted UBS AG and Bank of
America Merrill Lynch as joint corporate brokers, the Sunday
Times reported, without saying where it got the information. The
stock fell 0.8 percent to 249 pence.    John Wood Group Plc  (WG/ LN): General Electric Co. agreed
to buy the well-support division of the U.K. oil and gas
services company for about $2.8 billion. Wood Group’s shares
gained 3.3 percent to 572.5 pence.    National Express Group Plc  (NEX LN): The U.K. bus and rail
operator has not been asked by Elliot Management, which holds 16
percent in the company, to put itself up for sale and to explore
an alliance with Stagecoach Group Plc or Societe Nationale des
Chemins de Fer Francais, the Daily Telegraph reported, citing
National Express Chief Executive Officer Dean Finch. The stock
climbed 0.3 percent to 254.9 pence.    Rolls-Royce Group Plc  (RR/ LN): Chairman Simon Robertson
told leading investors that he intends to step down by the end
of next year, Mark Kleinman said in his column in the Financial
Times, without saying where he got the information. The stock
rose 1.2 percent to 657.5 pence.    Royal Bank of Scotland Group Plc  (RBS LN): The U.K.’s
biggest government-owned bank will not pay bonuses for last year
to as many as a third of employees in its global banking and
markets division, Mark Kleinman wrote in his column in the
Financial Times. The shares dropped 0.7 percent to 43.99 pence.    SVG Capital Plc  (SVI LN): The biggest backer of Permira
Advisers LLP said full-year net asset value per share increased
42 percent to 319 pence a share as of Dec. 31. The stock gained
1.4 percent to 247.4 pence.    Tesco Plc  (TSCO LN): The world’s fourth-largest retailer
plans to start a used-car dealership this year, the Mail on
Sunday reported. The shares rose 0.1 percent to 395.05 pence.    Vedanta Resources Plc  (VED LN): Konkola Copper Mines Plc, a
unit of Vedanta Resources, plans to spend as much as $50 million
on environmental projects in Zambia this year, Corporate Affairs
Manager Jacqueline Kabeta said. The stock rose 1.7 percent to
2,361 pence.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Blanche Gatt in London at 
